I suspect what needs to happen here is something like:

struct Threshold {
   Direction dir;
   Level level;
   const char* name;
}

constexpr std::array<Threshold, 4> thresholds = {
{Direction:HIGH, Level::CRITICAL, "CriticalHigh"},
{Direction:LOW, Level::CRITICAL, "CriticalLow"},
{Direction:HIGH, Level::WARNING, "WarningHigh"},
{Direction:LOW, Level::WARNING, "WarningLow"},
}


The above means that we're not constructing any per-sensor data structures at runtime.

Ack, I have split the array into 2, since threshold level is present in 2 rows and it is not able to identify which level needs to be read. 

    struct ThresholdLevel
    {
        thresholds::Level level;
        std::string levelProperty;
    };

    struct ThresholdDirection
    {
        thresholds::Direction direction;
        std::string alarmProperty;
    };

    std::array<Sensor::ThresholdLevel, 2> thresLevelProp = {
        {{thresholds::Level::WARNING, "Warning"},
         {thresholds::Level::CRITICAL, "Critical"}}};
    std::array<Sensor::ThresholdDirection, 2> thresAlarmProp = {
        {{thresholds::Direction::HIGH, "High"},
         {thresholds::Direction::LOW, "Low"}}};

You seem to have forgotten to range check these.  You can't just index into an array, and as written, you need to compare threshLevel[index].first against the level being given, considering it's part of the array.  If I reverse the order of the list above, which is legal to do, this code breaks.

I believe the above issue is why you thought these needed to be multiple tables.  Just iterate

for (prop: thresLevelProp){
    if (prop.level == lev && prop.direction == dir){
        return prop.levelProperty;
    }
}

return ""


That will both handle the range checks as part of the for loop, and handle errors properly, while keeping a single table, which is simpler.

Always init your variables.  With that said, in this case, I suspect you don't need the variable at all:

    if (order == "greater than")
    {
        return 0;
    }
    else if (order == "less than")
    {
        return 1;
    }
    return -1;

Which simplifies your code and removes the variable entirely.
